      "id":"books/2013/oct/03/inside-story-coalition-government-dancona-review",
      "sectionId":"books",
      "sectionName":"Books",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-03T14:00:02Z",
      "webTitle":"In It Together: The Inside Story of the Coalition Government by Matthew D'Ancona – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/oct/03/inside-story-coalition-government-dancona-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2013/oct/03/inside-story-coalition-government-dancona-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"9",
        "trailText":"How do Cameron, Osborne and Clegg really&nbsp;work together? By&nbsp;Gaby Hinsliff",
        "headline":"In It Together: The Inside Story of the Coalition Government by Matthew D'Ancona – review",
        "body":"<p>How do you tell a story, without yet knowing where it ends?</p><p>That's the challenge facing Matthew d'Ancona in this book, which represents the first really serious attempt at hitting the biggest moving target in contemporary politics. Like an&nbsp;impatient scientist trying to second‑guess an experiment before the&nbsp;test-tube has stopped fizzing, the&nbsp;author can inevitably draw only limited conclusions about a coalition that still has nearly two years to run. He can describe what he has seen in lurid, expletive-ridden detail, but can't&nbsp;yet be sure whether it changes the laws of electoral physics. Has this bold constitutional experiment actually worked? Does it have a future, after 2015? Has it changed the British political landscape and voters' expectations of government for good? You won't find definitive answers to such questions here.</p><p>But then in fairness, perhaps D'Ancona never really set out to provide them. The conscious model for this book is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/andrewrawnsley\" title=\"\">Andrew Rawnsley</a>'s rollicking <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/sep/30/politics\" title=\"\"><em>Servants of the People</em></a>, which relentlessly exposed the below-stairs shenanigans of the early Blair-Brown years, and if his aim was to serve up some similarly juicy gossip D'Ancona has succeeded. By comparison with the tortured psychological dramas of New Labour, the coalition inevitably seems almost Zen-like. But there's still some dirty linen to air, even if the best titbits – that the chancellor thinks welfare secretary Iain Duncan Smith is&nbsp;thick, that Boris Johnson vowed to quit politics after his second term as London mayor to \"go and earn some money\" – have already tumbled out in published extracts. And who knew Angela Merkel liked nothing better than watching old episodes of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/mar/17/tv-matters-midsomer-murders\" title=\"\"><em>Midsomer Murders</em></a>, so much so that Downing Street once tried (and failed) to engineer an unlikely meeting with actor John Nettles?</p><p>Yet what made the Rawnsley book indispensable is that all the muckraking illustrated a bigger truth; the relationship between Labour's prime minister and chancellor was so hideously dysfunctional that, with hindsight, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;a miracle that the government ever&nbsp;got out of bed in the&nbsp;morning. If&nbsp;the anecdotes in this book add up to&nbsp;anything bigger, it is less the inside story of the coalition – the Lib&nbsp;Dems appear mainly as bit players bumbling through someone else's drama – than a&nbsp;snapshot of one turbulent moment in&nbsp;Conservative history. And the dominant figure isn't David Cameron but George Osborne, portrayed here as the political and economic heart of this administration.</p><p>On paper, there are few journalists better placed to make such judgment calls. D'Ancona is one of the shrewdest, most engaging observers of the Cameron phenomenon, yet, unusually among rightwing columnists, he takes the other parties seriously too. He is&nbsp;an&nbsp;insider's insider, having known Michael Gove since Oxford and most of&nbsp;the set around Cameron since their 20s. But then, as he points out, this government is intensely social: they're friends who fell into politics together, rather than politicians whose friendships were forged through the party.</p><p>The book certainly gets the cliquey, breezy, carefree Cameron vibe that so infuriates MPs outside the inner circle; the sense that they are just a gang of mates on a marvellously exciting adventure from which they could walk&nbsp;away if necessary: after all, their friendships will likely endure, even if&nbsp;the <em>grand projet</em> doesn't. As D'Ancona says of Osborne's decision to swan off to Washington with the prime minister days before what would become the \"omnishambles\" budget, the chancellor might be a Roundhead on policy but \"he was a Cavalier by temperament, determined to experience everything that politics had to offer … the choice between going to America to hang out&nbsp;with Obama or lingering in London to monitor Twitter and the blogs in case of budget leaks was no choice at all.\" What larks! Yet one wonders if Tory MPs in marginal seats, still smarting from the damage done by pasty taxes, would agree with D'Ancona's generous verdict that the budget trainwreck probably wouldn't have been avoided even if Osborne had stayed at the helm. And therein lies an awkward problem.</p><p>The book skips oddly lightly over episodes that were not Osborne's finest hour. If the chancellor harbours any regrets – or his colleagues had any recriminations – about that shambolic budget, or his failure to reduce the deficit on target, they are barely examined here. Similarly, when the crowd at the Olympic stadium boos Osborne, it is presented not as a&nbsp;humiliation but a testament to his steeliness, in comparison with the shamelessly cheap, populist Boris. (D'Ancona's fascinating analysis of the rivalry between mayor and chancellor, more bitter and yet less examined than Boris's relationship with the prime minister, reads like an essential primer for the next Tory leadership contest.)</p><p>By comparison with such insights, the Lib Dem side of the story feels almost two-dimensional. \"Needy Nick\", as the Lib Dem leader is dubbed early on by exasperated Tory colleagues, emerges as a faintly petulant figure, and business secretary Vince Cable as an irritant to pretty much everyone. We get little sense of who Danny Alexander is beyond his closeness to&nbsp;his boss, the chancellor. The spectacular downfall of Chris Huhne is&nbsp;shoehorned a little awkwardly into a&nbsp;chapter on gay marriage. And while the subsequent by-election in his seat was a turning point for Clegg – the moment at which his MPs began to believe the next election needn't inevitably wipe them out – in this book <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2013/mar/01/eastleigh-byelection-results-2013\" title=\"\">Eastleigh</a> becomes mainly a cautionary tale about the rise of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/ukip\" title=\"\">Ukip</a>.</p><p>What is perhaps more surprising, however, is that Cameron also emerges as a rather lonely and elusive figure, defined largely in the space between his great friend Osborne and his great rival Boris. He clings for so long to his damaged press secretary <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/andy-coulson\" title=\"\">Andy Coulson</a> at least partly because, D'Ancona writes, he \"did not make close friends easily\". Besieged on all sides by furious&nbsp;Tory backbenchers, whingeing Lib&nbsp;Dems, pesky Ukip and sly old Boris, one wonders at times why he bothers. Would he go into coalition again?</p><p>D'Ancona doesn't directly address the question, but it is clear from the odd aside that Cameron's determination to keep Clegg on board reflects, at least partly, the feeling that he might be needed a second time. There are glimpses too, of what a post-2015 round of horsetrading might look like. D'Ancona describes a set of welfare reform negotiations in which Clegg says his price for agreeing more benefit cuts would be reducing handouts to&nbsp;wealthy pensioners, something Cameron glumly describes as \"my tuition fees\". But we learn little more about how both sides might disentangle themselves from coalition, or what they expect to happen next.</p><p>Perhaps it is too early to say. The election is still 19 months away and events are unfolding unpredictably and at great speed. But if journalism is&nbsp;the first rough draft of history, then such books must at least be a fairly advanced revision, stepping back from the sound and fury to place events in their broader context. D'Ancona has certainly gathered together an impressive pile of jigsaw pieces. But the picture remains far from complete.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418962015|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|986c993f300786b4289056584559ac08bc07bc3e -->",
