        "trailText":"David Plante's diary of his friendship with Stephen Spender is a powerful portrait of love set in the liberal London of the 60s, writes <strong>Lara Feigel</strong>",
        "headline":"Becoming a Londoner: A Diary by David Plante – review",
        "body":"<p>When David Plante began to write his diary in 1966, he was self-consciously in dialogue with Stephen Spender. At this stage the 26-year-old aspiring American novelist knew the older poet only by proxy. Plante had read Spender's memoir <em>World Within World</em> and had stolen his lover, the sculpturally beautiful Greek poet <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/apr/30/guardianobituaries.booksobituaries1\" title=\"\">Nikos Stangos</a>. In early diary entries, Plante speculated about when he and Spender would cross paths. Within weeks, they were friends. Spender adopted the young couple, introduced them to a staggering quantity of famous men and quickly became their closest ally. Plante was not introduced to Spender's wife, Natasha.</p><p>A few months into the friendship, Spender set off to plant trees in Natasha's garden in France. He secretly took Plante with him, presenting him to luminaries including Francis Bacon and Louis Aragon in Paris along the way. Spender found it characteristically hilarious that someone called Plante was planting trees for him. He doesn't seem to have found it especially problematic that these were Natasha's trees that he was conspiratorially planting with a young man. The two men even shared a room, although the beds were carefully placed apart.</p><p>It is sad but not surprising that this episode is absent from Spender's own journals. Instead of writing about it, Spender made sure that Plante was recording it for him. \"You can put this in your diary,\" Spender says early on. Plante correctly wonders \"if he wants me to write in my diary events in his life that he himself would not write in&nbsp;his\". So Plante's diary emerges as the story left out of Spender's more carefully self-censored journals. And&nbsp;Spender becomes the central character in a diary that he orchestrates, both by&nbsp;staging the events and by commanding that they be recorded. \"What worlds within worlds am I living&nbsp;in?\" Plante asks.</p><p>It is Plante and Stangos's relationship with the Spenders that gives this book its narrative drive. As is often the case in diaries, most of the action is episodic. The cast is impressive: there is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/bacon\" title=\"\">Francis Bacon</a> in the Colony Room, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/whauden\" title=\"\">WH Auden</a> buying carpet slippers in the Strand, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/philiproth\" title=\"\">Philip Roth</a> and Claire Bloom. But in selecting from his diaries, Plante seems to have decided that the momentum of&nbsp;the book should come from his relationship with Stangos and the couple's relationship with the Spenders. This was a good decision – it&nbsp;saves the book from reading as a catalogue of lunching and dining, and creates the sense of a plot unfolding. At&nbsp;first Spender is scrupulous about keeping the young men apart from his&nbsp;wife; it transpires that she is angry&nbsp;when he sees them. When he commissions a painting of them naked in bed, he rushes home to hide it. Phone conversations are interrupted by a click on the line informing them that Natasha has been ostentatiously listening in upstairs.</p><p>Then after about 10 years (frustratingly almost no dates are given), Plante bumps into Natasha at&nbsp;a&nbsp;party. She is in the middle of a conversation; Plante interrupts to introduce himself; Natasha pretends never to have heard his name before. Plante is left awkwardly interjecting \"how nice!\" at regular intervals while Natasha and her friend studiously ignore him. Here begins a social game in which Natasha out-manoeuvres Plante, Stangos and her husband. Shortly afterwards, the two couples meet at another party and Natasha moves from ignoring him to charm. Stangos is about to go into hospital to&nbsp;have a rectal polyp removed. Apparently unembarrassed, Natasha inquires in detail about the operation, urging him to arm himself with an eye-mask and to call on her assistance. Within weeks Plante and Stangos are&nbsp;guests in her home, pretending uncomfortably they have&nbsp;never been there before.</p><p>A wholly new picture of the Spenders' marriage materialises. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/03/stephen-spender-journals-feigel-review\" title=\"\">Having co-edited Spender's journals</a>, I&nbsp;assumed that he would have left Natasha if he'd been more courageous. But the madness was obviously a folie à deux. Natasha needs her husband to affirm her saintliness by testing the limits of her love; Stephen needs his wilful wife to set down rather absurd boundaries for him to transgress. Hence the intrusiveness of her surveillance, the clumsiness of his lies&nbsp;and the ill-thought-out gifts (at one&nbsp;point Spender gives Plante one of their&nbsp;Picassos, instructing him to hide it if Natasha visits). Plante assumes that he and Stangos are exploiting the Spenders and potentially damaging their marriage; in fact perhaps the Spenders need the younger couple to&nbsp;enliven their own marital games.</p><p>The book also offers a window on to a changing world. \"I wish that when I&nbsp;was your age I had had what you have now with Nikos,\" Spender tells Plante. He believes that happy gay love was impossible for his generation. Instead he takes a vicarious pleasure in the happiness of the young. In their early years together, Plante and Stangos occasionally remember that they are technically criminals, but find that \"it is as if all the conventions of sex and clothes and art and music and drink and drugs don't apply here in London\". This wasn't true for Spender, and the sense of an older, more formal and class-based world giving way to a new order is movingly portrayed.</p><p>The book is also powerful as a portrait of mutual love. Plante has come to Europe seeking promiscuity; instead, he is surprised into monogamous happiness. \"Is this love?\" he asks. \"Is it love to want to be with him when he dies, and close his eyes?\" And Plante is generous in seeing Spender as&nbsp;the creator of all that is best in this relationship: \"in discovering the world he has opened to us we are discovering one another.\"</p><p>• Lara Feigel's <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9781408830444\" title=\"\"><em>The Love-charm of Bombs: Restless Lives in the Second World War</em></a> is published by Bloomsbury.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418628795|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|237bca40536c296b4803ac6072a4112116518a36 -->",
